At 07:17 AM 08/17/2002, you wrote:
>   I just don't want to remove the whole shifter assembly, go through
>the mysteries of getting it all back together right, then have my shifting
>end up being even worse (which is what I keep reading here).
>
>Also, if it turns out that I DO need to remove the shifter, is getting it
>all back together right (and being able to shift properly afterwards)=
 really
>as involved and difficult as it sounds?


Remove the rubber floor mat completely. Pull up the boot. Vacuum the junk=20
from around the shift plate. Wire brush it and clean thoroughly. Use a=20
scribe to outline the plate position for reinstallation, then pull the two=
=20
bolts and pull up the shifter. Carefull not to lose the pin and spring.=20
Remove the cross bolt and bushings from the shift link at the rear. Push=20
the rear shift rod back into the trans. Now you can move the front, long=20
shift rod back and have just enough room to install the front bushing.=20
Note: there are two types of front bushings, an early type and later type.=
=20
I think the split was 74. Bentley only shows the earlier version. Don't let=
=20
that bother you, just order the bushing for your model year. Pull the rear=
=20
shift rod back out to the neutral position and reinstall the link parts.

Clean and grease and reinstall the shifter. A bit of care is needed to get=
=20
the pin with it's small spring seated within the ball and socket. Pushing=20
down against the big plate spring, reinstall the bolts and adjust the plate=
=20
to the original scribed lines. Test the shift pattern. If it was shifting=20
properly before the bushing wore out, it will likely be just fine. If there=
=20
is any problem finding gears, you then must loosed the bolts and move the=20
plate a bit and try again. You may need to do this several times until you=
=20
find a good position, but it takes but a moment to make each trial=20
adjustment of the shift plate. Book procedure is to put it in 2nd gear then=
=20
adjust the plate so the lower part of the shifter is 90=B0 to the floor.=
 This=20
only works if the shift plate is not too worn. If it is worn, replace it as=
=20
they don't cost much.=20

